{"actual_usd":0.157075,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":255,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30650,"reply":"\"No—he didn’t become God’s Son at his baptism.\" *I rest a thumb in the worn edge of my Bible and glance up at the bright morning lying across the square stones.* \"He was always the Son, and he did not become divine at any point. He is eternal—'In the beginning was the Word,' as John says, and that Word was with God and was God.\"\n\n*I shift my weight a little, the bench giving a soft creak under me.* \"His baptism was a revealing, not a promotion. The Father’s voice—'This is my beloved Son'—was not making Jesus into something new. It was declaring what had always been true. Same with his divinity: Christians don’t believe Jesus started out as a mere man and then got upgraded. We believe the eternal Son took on flesh. Fully God, and then truly man as well.\"\n\n\"If you want the old church-word for the wrong idea, adoptionism is the one—Jesus as a man adopted into sonship later. The Church rejected that because it doesn’t fit the witness of Scripture.\" *I give you a small, sympathetic look.* \"Were you asking because of a specific verse, or just trying to get the timeline straight?\"","rolling_24h_usd":36.31816500000002,"run_id":"4cdb3024-daea-4c28-b41e-bcdf6f661be6"}
